The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                        NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	Jaipur, Aug. 3 (PTI): A woman today allegedly set on fire wads of currency notes amounting to Rs 5 lakh and burnt herself to death as her husband had refusal to lend Rs 500 to her brother.          
	Husband Kishore Singhs refusal to oblige his brother-in-law sparked heated arguments between Suman and Singh, police said. Later, Kishore allegedly thrashed Suman which prompted her to take the extreme step, the police added.                   
	New Delhi: The arrest of a 23-year-old man who used a forged security pass to allegedly pose as a Delhi police constable attached with the security wing of the Prime Minister has sent senior police officials into a tizzy ahead of the Independence Day. Vikas was caught on Singhu border picket in Outer Delhi on Sunday evening when he showed the security pass to the cops.                   
	New Delhi (PTI): An automobile company and its dealer have been directed by a consumer court to pay a man Rs 40,000 in damages for harassing him physically and mentally when he came to get noise and vibration problems in his new car rectified.                   
	Aligarh (PTI): The Aligarh Muslim University is planning to set up an Indo-US energy centre here following discussions with American special envoy Rashad Hussain, officials said on Tuesday.                   
	Mumbai (PTI): Prakash Mahajan, brother of the late BJP leader Pramod Mahajan, has claimed his share in a plot given to a trust run by Pramods daughter. Prakash said he would undertake an indefinite fast to claim his share in the 3.5-acre plot given to the trust seven years ago.                   
	New Delhi (PTI): Tihar jail has given Rs 60,000 to 11 victims of crime as part of its victim welfare fund, established on the orders of the Supreme Court.
                                                                                                                                              
